g.ns192:text:
{\centering
{\Large\bfseries \xbfPor qu\xe9 aparecen los t\xe9rminos ``extra'' en la aceleraci\xf3n polar?}

\vspace{0.5em}

$\frac{\Delta\hat{e}_r}{\Delta t} \approx \frac{\Delta\varphi}{\Delta t}\cdot\hat{e}_\varphi \rightarrow \frac{d\hat{e}_r}{dt} = \dot{\varphi}\cdot\hat{e}_\varphi$ del mismo modo: $\frac{d\hat{e}_\varphi}{dt} = -\dot{\varphi}\cdot\hat{e}_r$

\vspace{0.3em}

Al derivar $\dot{r} = \dot{r}\cdot\hat{e}_r + r\dot{\varphi}\cdot\hat{e}_\varphi$ → el t\xe9rmino $-r\dot{\varphi}^2$ viene de: $r\dot{\varphi}\cdot\left(\frac{d\hat{e}_\varphi}{dt}\right) = r\dot{\varphi}\cdot(-\dot{\varphi}\cdot\hat{e}_r)$
}
